annotation: I can't believe I went through another never-before-encountered opening the Queen pawn Lundin defence.
white is weak but is trying to demolish my pawn/knight structure
Two attempts but white has not taken my knight.
somehow the bishop/pawn structure failed to prevail. Retreat is almost impossible.
by not retreating white has a lost game. Can you see how I can pulverize white.
this move gives up my knight for a pulverized game.
this LATE retreat invites black to follow up a series of unstoppable checks. White probably could have tried 20.Rd1 instead.
White should have tried 21.Qf2 to stop this.
22.g4?? or 22.Qf3. 22.g4?? is a waste of time. Sadly if white thinks he has time to distract me at this point he will be astonished by these shocking next moves.
22...Qxe4+!! makes this mate unstoppable.
This is an example of what not to do with a great opening.

Here is another annotation from me and the reason I annotated it is because of another mate (thanks to maestro and his pamphlets) on how to improve my game I sat down and planned out this mate from move 19 (yes thats only 6 moves ahead) but to me thats a significant improvement and I'd like you guys to see it
Here we see White in a slightly better position Black opening a white diagnoal on his King but White also doing the same for the Black Queen
Taking control of the centre Nb3 d5 or Bf4 may have been better
Heavily restricting Blacks LSB here..

Possibly opening up more squares for his LSB? I didnt see it as a real smart move stopping d6 maybe to stop opening up a line on his King? But d6 then causes Bxe4 which loses my momentum so that wasnt happening
Bringing the White Bishop into play after I blocked its usual path..
It was here I couldnt tell how but I could see a vague stronghold I could gain with both the Bishop and Queen coming together around d7
Maybe e6 would have ben smarter? That gives Black no more pawn with which to defend and gives White an outpost for white Bishop with Be6+
Check!

With the Queen threatening would g6 have been a better move for the King? I know g6 Nf4 leads to some serious problems leaving him with h7 but Bf5 g6 Bxg6 is the continuation I found then the King has g7 to move to and it looks a lot less bleak in my opinion...
Noticed another free spot for my Knight to occupy at least temporarily
Black has got to be running scared here....just a few moves away from mate no tempo no development I was extrememly happy with what I was sure was going to be the outcome..

A point I thought worth noticing was 11....Qe8 Black moves his Queen IN LINE with White's Queen as to threaten it although covered by the Knight on c3 at the time but as you will see when White threatens it Black shys away...it just made me think a little more
Hmm...whethere it was d8 or e8 in move 11 or e7/e8 here it was still protecting the d7 square as was the Knight and that square was my goal
I started to see a new oppertunity once Black allowed White to gain control of b6 and essentially dig deeper into his now almost depleted defenses
Was expecting g5 sooner or later maybe even h5 to try create an escape route for the Black King

I thought Black may play Nd7? The White Bishop cannot take for losing his Queen and although the Knight isnt doing much on d7 the Queen has to move (probably to c7) and the Rook has the Back line to play along and probably assist the Black Queen
A good move I thought bringing the Knight in and of course the Queen is doing nothing wrong defending it
However leaving the pawn undefended and by the move/s previous to this when I deliberating the Rook exchange I had seen a mate which was very likely

I had planned in this (one thing my analysis usually lacks is the "best move" for the oppenent) I plan a line but usually I miss a move that the opponent could make that is better for him/her...so pleased with this so far

Had considered into my plans Nd7 or e7 at this stage surely Black understands that to make White play this game out further a Queen exchange was most likely the only thing to temporarily stop the mate..
Now I knew mate was guaranteed and delighted as such
King has nowhere to go

And there is it. Mate. Happy that I found it and more importantly that I was able to seize control of the game and not let it go. Compared to those that saw my previous annotation where there was a chance for White to take the Black bishop on h5 with my Queen but didnt and although I won it prolonged mate which was maybe 3 or 4 moves away...whereas this time I didnt let up or let it slip I was in control and played accordingly.

Comments appreciated!

I play e4 pretty much exclusively as it fits my style of play (aggressive attacking).  Certainly there are many good first moves for white.  Players of e4 must be prepared to face a very wide array of black responses including the standard e5 and it's ensuing variations as well as the Sicilian (tons of lines!) the French Scandinavian etc.
A very common response to 1. e4 leading to some of the most popular openings among GMs today including Petroff and Ruy Lopez to name two.
Natural play developing and attacking the pawn.
Again natural play.

More common moves are Nc3 and Bb5 (Ruy Lopez or Spanish).  I typically play Bc4 because it fits my aggressive playing style and can lead to many gambit lines.  I find opponents at my level are often less familiar with how to proceed facing this move than the other two.
The natural move reaching the Two Knights Defense.

There are many available moves here such as Nc3 and d3 which are solid but a bit too stodgy for my personal style.  The move I played appears to lose a pawn but after Nxe4 black can not actual retain the pawn advantage.  White can play 5. Re1 or 5. Bd5 and regain the pawn in short order.  One of the reasons I play O-O is to give black the chance to play Bb5 a common move that leads to variations I enjoy playing (such as the Max Lange attack).  Other move options include 4. d4!? which is the original Max Lange gambit and of course 4. Ng5 for the the infamous Fried Liver Attack!  Perhaps Hurnavich would disagree but personally I think that the Fried Liver is a great opening for beginning and intermediate players to look at because it helps develop tactical thinking and an understanding of mating attacks.  One thing is sure you will face it sooner or later as black if you play the Two Knights!
The most direct move to regain the pawn.  Re1 also effective.
Retreating to f6 is the best move.
Bxc6 ensures that white will recoup the pawn.
I have had opponents play bxc6 but I feel dxc6 is better.  It gives both the queen and the light-squared bishop more scope on the board.

Nxe5 capturing the pawn.  Assessing this position I would have to say white has not accomplished anything significant from the opening.  White is not worse but certainly not better.  Perhaps the 4. Nc3 line suggested by Iansky is more promising.
Definitely the strongest and most natural continuation.

Defends the knight and allows for the development of the dark bishop.  Re1 would be premature as after BxN RxB white has a misplaced rook that will have to be moved again; meanwhile his other minor pieces are sitting on the back rank.
Castling is certainly a reasonable move here.  BxN is playable but it is to black's advantage to hang on to the bishop pair.
Develops a piece and creates and pins the knight.  White is fantasizing about playing Qf3 and then Nd2 and Ne4.  Of course there are a lot of moves on black's part but that is the working plan.

This move does break the pin but I prefer it's prior position on d6 eying the h2 square.  It does thwart the plan of Qf3 etc for white.  I think better would have been to continue development with Be6 or to challenge the bishop with h6.
White develops his last piece putting pressure on d5 and e4.  White will be looking next to centralize the queen with a move such as Qd3 followed by bringing the rooks to the central files.
Good move completing development and placing the bishop on an active square.
Centralizing the queen and connecting the rooks.

Places knight on a good post but does give white the option of eliminating black's bishop pair.  It's hard to suggest a significantly better move.  Perhaps Re1 placing the rook on an open file (no pawns).

I think capturing with the queen would be better as this retreats the knight to a less active square.  Also capturing with the queen would connect the rook and get the queen out of the way to bring them into the center as needed.
Knight returns to it's better post.  I think this is the best move but it emphasizes black's loss of time in capturing with the N on the previous move.

White is not anxious to trade down pieces further since that would lead fairly quickly to a drawn position.  This move puts the N on a very active central square and moves it closer to the enemy king.
Black elects to trade down further which is probably fine.  Black will have to be careful that white does not mount too much pressure on his king-side however.

This move attacks the R and brings a piece closer to the king to aid in defense.  Just to note that this knight has now made a circuit from f6-d5-e7-d5-f6.  That is a lot of moves for one piece and as a result black still has queen and rook in starting position while white has queen and rook active.

Threatening Rxh6 and generally threatening mayhem on black's king-side.  White has to keep in mind the black queen x-raying the rook through the black night but there is no danger in that regard at present.
The best and I think only good move to deal with Rh4.
Activating the final piece in white's arsenal.  White will be looking to increase pressure on black's king.

While a move like this is tempting to pressure the rook it doesn't turn out well for black.  Black had a fairly safe king-side structure prior to this move and dramatic pawn moves in front of the king should only be made with very careful consideration.  In this case the problem for black is that the pawn on h6 is pinned by white's rook so although the pawn advanced to g5 appears to be guarded it in fact is not.  Black needed to look for ways to get his queen and a8 rook into the game.
Serious trouble now for black with white threatening Rxh6# next move.
Qf8 would have held temporarily.
Removing the defender of the queen with check.  Removing the defender of a piece is always worth investigating.  In this case the result is crushing.
Tartakower plays aggressively using the From Gambit.
The gambit must be accepted. However this opens an avenue of attack for Tartakower along the KB file.

The usual move is 4 B-KN5 but Tartakower springs a novelty. Mieses misses the best response [4... P-KR3]. Alekhine used the "opening surprise" method throughout his career to great success so Tartakower borrows a page from his playbook.
Forcing the Knight back to its original square.
Practically forcing Mieses' reply as 6... B-B4 7 PxP PxP 8 B-QB4 is virtually a won game for White.
Applying pressure along the open KB file. With ...N-KB3 impossible Mieses has no effective way to block an invasion along this route.
To prevent 9 Q-R5 ch.
Clearing the Rook's path to KB1 augmenting the attack.
Black has to defend the natural invasion spot at his KB2.
Throwing another piece forward. White's lead in development is immense.
To close off B-N5 ch.
Attacking the immobilized KR.
Forced.
Now threatening to win the QN. White's superior mobility and ability to attack the whole board are causing Black's defenses to crumble.
12... N-Q2 would at least threaten to exchange a pair of minor pieces. Black's position is hopeless in any case.
Bringing yet another piece into the attack.
Black desperately tries to stem the oncoming tidal wave.
Forcing away the Queen.
The only square.
Mieses resigns. White's two mating threats [16 Q-B7 mate and 16 Q-B8 ch! BxQ 17 RxB mate] cannot be parried without ruinous loss of material.
Maroczy plays a most unusual response to Forgacs' opening thrust.
Maroczy plays a delayed French defense.
Maroczy intends to apply pressure to Forgacs' pawn chain and break it.
Both players begin developing their pieces after the flurry of initial Pawn moves.
Trying to pressure Forgacs' Q-side where Maroczy has a spatial edge. Forgacs' play should lie on the K-side with this Pawn formation.
Maroczy has accomplished his triplet of achievements. Now it is Forgacs' turn.
The only square.
Countering the threat of discovered check with an attack on the B.
Seizing the loose pawn and creating a passed QRP.
Threatening Forgacs' Q. but the Hungarian master is unafraid.
Setting up what's almost like an exchange of Queens except that instead of both Queens being captured the taken Queen reincarnates.
Forced.
Allowing the B to interpose if Forgacs' Q checks on the 8th rank.
Now that both sides have finished their remarkable achievements Maroczy plays to swarm Forgacs' position for the win.
Making air for his King.
Placing his King in a safe haven and allowing him to launch the final attack.
Looking for a "skewer" to win the Rook.
The winning move.
With decisive material gain.
Forgacs resigns.
The amateur opens with the QP hoping to prolong his resistance by playing a positional slow game.
Bruening counters in Classical style.
The standard reply.
Bruening plays an Orthodox defense in response.
The amateur forgets the rule: Knights before Bishops. 3 N-QB3 is the move he should make.
Bruening takes advantage of this with an immediate challenge to the center.
One move too late. Now Bruening can do...
...this in response.
The best move was to retreat the QN.
Now Bruening's advanced Pawn becomes threatening.
6 R-N1 or 6 PxP would drag out the game a bit.
Threatens PxR (Q) and B-N5 ch winning the White Q. White cannot defend both threats so he resigns at once.
Played to put me off... 3. Nc3 is normal but there's nothing wrong with this.
The fianchetto variation has caused me problems in the past and sets the King's Indian player a whole set of different challenges from other variations.
Going into a sort of Benoni always a choice for the KI player if he doesn't fancy ...e5 today.
An old-fashioned approach I first learnt from Harry Golombek's "Instructions to Young Chessplayers" when I was a young lad.  The Modern Benoni approach would be ...e6.
Now I regretted not having preceded ...Na6 with ...a5.
I decided to block the position so that I could continue my Queenside operations without worrying about the centre.  If White took en passant I was happy to recapture on e6 with the B attacking c4.
After the series of exchanges Black's position feels much more comfortable.
Puts immediate pressure on b2 and prepares to triple up on the b-file but the Q and rear rook are in the wrong formation for maximum effect.
So Black starts to reorganise
White discourages Black's N from joining in the attack on b4.
Black clears c5 for use by pieces but I was worried about the pawn becoming vulnerable.
? Failing to see White's simple reply I thought it would be useful to prevent the b-pawn from moving by blocking it.
This threw me into deep thought but eventually I couldn't find anything better than ceding the pawn for pressure on the c-file.
This looks a bit random but I was desperate to prevent White from playing Be3 when I'd lose what little initiative I had.
White guards against back-row mates that could occur in some lines.
I'd originally planned ...h6 but this looked more powerful either gaining control of an important diagonal or swapping the weak B for a stronger one.
White follows suit....
Now White has the potential for a quick kingside assault: hardly my intention when I played 21 ... Ng4
White's N hastens to the attack threatening Nf5+.  Compare this steed with Black's hapless nag stuck on the edge at a6.
Black defends the Nf6 so that when the check comes the K retreat doesn't lose it.
breaks the pin but sets up potential forks from f7.  Still better than 27...Kf8 28. Qh6+ Ke8 29. Ng7+ Ke7 30. Re3 Nc7 31. Rf3 Nce8 when Black is tangled up in abject defence.
Unexpected but White felt he had better prospects on the queenside now.
Now I felt much better....
White's bishop returns to defensive duties.

When we analysed the game afterwards I remembered rejecting capturing on b3 as too risky but couldn't demonstrate why it was.  We felt that perhaps I should have played 30....Nxb3 here.   ...Qe7 reduces the risk of forks from f7 but leaves the Rb8 undefended.
Time to get rid of the irritant on h6.
Now White's pawn advantage is looking even better.  He has more space and more active pieces.  How was I going to counter-attack?
It was essential not to cede control of the c-file.  This move defends the Rc7 while attacking e4.
White centralises his Q defending the pawn.
Offering up the a-pawn for the e-pawn.  I was convinced I had to play as actively as possible or lose meekly.
but there seemed nothing better for now than defending the pawn after all.
Looks like a strongpoint but at this stage the B is required for more active play than statically waiting for his pawns to catch up.
?! allows Black to give check and transform his prospects but White's attacking plans aren't through yet.
Now if White were to swap Black would threaten to quickly queen the passed central pawn.
White avoids the swap and reoccupies the c1-h6 diagonal.
Played with a view to delivering checkmate.
back onto the Bishop's best diagonal.
and enabling White's Q to commence his own mating attack.
Now White has to keep checking to stop Black from winning.
Black implicitly offers a draw by repetition.
I was surprised that White didn't take the opportunity but Black has no immediately useful check and White is seeking checkmate.
?  Surprisingly we found out afterwards thanks to my clubmate that 54...Kg8 55.Qd8+ Kh7! won for Black.  It was instinctive but wrong to duck behind the f-pawn again

Okay we're starting with a Kings Gambit.  So white wants a swashbuckling good time and he's willing to give black a slight advantage for it.  At this level of play this opening is quite a good choice.

In doing this you are a move ahead in the exact same attack.  You have the same weakness Q check with a pawn on the f file to create complications.  Accepting the pawn would have had white trade the weakness for his initiative but you have effectively equaled the weaknesses and given him even more initiative.

Here the mirroring had to stop if just from a tactical standpoint.  Qh5 is coming and it's not going to be pretty.  This is time for one of those really uncomfortable lines.  3...Qe7 4.Qh5+ Kd8 your king is going to have to move either way.  It's better to put him in the best square.  lets look at the alternative

White choose to play a swashbuckling game but forgot his sword.  Black should have played Qe7+ then Kd8 again getting his king out of dodge before allowing the true power of whites attack to come to fruit.  He has lost some pawns by not doing it sooner but their is still time.  5.Nf6?? it appears both players missed the tactic.  6.g7+ 7.Nxh5 8.g7xh8Q and white trades a pawn for a rook.
What about 7d4? instead of whats next. No need to trade just yet.  But okay white traded queens.

Look at the difference if white had already moved d4.  Note that in capturing f4 you also still have an attack on c7 if black is to capture.  Not suggesting capturing or not just saying the oppourtunity is there rather than this position.  In between moves can give you tiny advantages like that.

Again I like 8...hxg6 getting rid of that pesky pawn and opening things up a little bit for the rook on h8 whether it be on the h g or f file.  9.Bxg6 9...Kd8.  Anyways now black has a pesky pawn to deal with he has given up the option of taking it with a pawn and so no white can keep it there.
What about Ne2 attacking the pawn?  Get black to start tying up his pieces to defend his isolated pawn.  Lets count how many moves he spends on this knight.
I see white has a problem with bringing only one soldier to the war at a time.  Maybe 10.0-0 and you have a rook to help matters.  That's two moves for that knight

11...Nbd7 working on getting those rooks connected and your king off to the other side of the board seems just slightly better.  However pushing that knight back and showing white how much time they wasted is very tempting too.  However I favor bringing a new piece in that trades off rather than moving an old one twice to push a piece back especially since now the knight is eyeing g5.
3 moves for that knight

Maybe 12.Bd7 first stoping the knight checks the bishop and then forking the rook and bishop mess where black loses his bishop pair and doubles isolated pawns giving him four islands of isolated pawns.

But white has no interest in taking advantage of positional weaknesses.  Now he decides to castle.  Also note that 13.Nb5 is pretty cool.  That way when you do the whole trap with the bishop and pawns you have further forking threats.  Nevermind that though white decides to castle.
Black begins his attack
Four moves for that knight
make that five
Now we have 6
that's 7 moves with the knight just to trade it off?
Black checkmates while white is frolicking around on with it's horsey

!? On one hand this move is admirable for how it restricts Black's pieces and kicks the Black Knight out of d4. At this point during the next few moves we see a familiar pattern: One player makes a mistake then the other player after taking a big advantage doesn't know what to do with it and drifts aimlessly. "E4 best by test!" - R. Fischer
Defends e5 and allows light bishop to develop; blocks development of dark bishop and loses some time as it is not developing a piece.  Better Nc6 or Nf6 (Petroff's defense).
Rapid piece development eyes naturally weak f7 square allows for king side castling.  Other strong moves would include Nc3 (developing) and d4 directly challenging the center.
Strong move as it develops a piece and attacks white pawn in the center.

Developing move that protects e4.  At first blush seems to blunder into 4. ... Nxe4  5. Nxe4 d5 with a piece fork.  However after 4. ... Nxe4 the intermezzo move 5. Bxf7+ Kxf7 6. Nxe4 gives white the advantage (white with lead in development black unable to castle).

This move perhaps is motivated by a desire to challenge the center and/or the white light-squared bishop.  However it is a mistake for a few reasons.  First it does not develop a piece.  Remember it is paramount to develop the minor pieces as quickly as possible in the opening.  Second it is best not to move a piece (or pawn) twice in the opening unless there is a compelling reason.  Third after 5. exd5 black will simply lose this pawn.  Much better would have been 4. ... Be7 preparing to castle or Bg4 setting up a pin against the white queen.
Bxd5 also possible but why give up a well-placed bishop?
Good developing move that pins the white knight and threatens e4 on the following move.

There are a few options to meet the threat of e4.  Perhaps the strongest would be to "put the question" to the black bishop by playing h3.  However if black then continues with e4 anyway after hxg4 white's king-side pawns will be a bit disrupted.  I elected to play d3 which nullifies the threat of e4 and allows an exit for the dark bishop.  Another playable move would be Qe2.
Strong developing move pinning an important white piece protecting the d5 pawn and putting pressure on the center.  Threatens to win back the d5 pawn.
Develops the bishop and breaks the pin.  If 7. ... Bxc3  8. Bxc3 black can win the d5 pawn with Nxc5 but white will remain up a pawn after Bxe5.
Probably the best move.
Completes development and improves king safety.
Solid move completing development and protecting e5 pawn.
Various playable moves including Re1 and h3.  This move was chosen to force trade down of pieces while maintaining the pawn advantage.

This is black's strongest option and better than Nxe4.  Nxe4 would allow dxe4 where white supports the e5 pawn giving him a strong center.  After the played move Bxd2 white must decide between capturing with the knight he just moved and capturing with the queen.

I have elected to avoid the doubled f pawns that could arise after 10. Qxd2 Bxf3.  It should be noted that doubled f pawns are not necessarily a weakness and are often preferred by players such as Nigel Short.  One advantage for white would be the possibility of putting a rook on the half-open g file applying pressure towards the black king.  However the doubled f pawns can make the white king vulnerable (not everyone is as expert at defending as Nigel Short including me!) so I have captured with the knight.

This move prepares for b5 pressuring white's bishop.  However the bishop will have a safe retreat to b3 anyway.  Black would be on the verge of winning back the pawn on d5 with a more aggressive move such as Nb6.
Black's prior move a6 allows white time to retreat the bishop preparing for c4.  Another option would be to move the queen from behind the pin.

Moves rook to the center supporting e5 and helping prepare for possible push to e4 at some point.  Centralizing rooks and/or placing them on open or half-open files is a good general theme to remember after completing minor piece development.

Forces black to make a decision regarding the pinning bishop while creating luft for the white king with tempo.  The timing of if and when to create space for your king can be a tricky thing.  Too early and you can neglect development giving your opponent the edge.  Too late and you can find yourself with serious back-rank problems.  Another good move would have been Re1 shoring up against the threat of e4.
Centralizing the rook and placing it on the half-open file.

This would have been strong on move 10 instead of a6 but here it really just allows white to proceed with his plan to play c4.  Perhaps better would have been Nc5 after which black will have the option of capturing the light-squared bishop ( if 13. ... Nc5 Bc4 then b5 forces bishop back ).
This move solidifies the d5 pawn which up to this point has been fairly weak and a good target for black.  It also creates a space for the white queen to step out from behind the pin to c2.

At this stage of the game moving the queen to a more central position and connecting the rooks is a very good thought.  You must take care though not to place the queen in a position where it can be attacked by minor pieces.  In this case white can play Ne4 next if he chooses with the option of further trading down pieces.  White's plan has been to step out of the pin to c2 and we see now that he can do this with tempo as it threatens c5 next forking the knight and queen.  ( For any following we just discovered Paul was unaware of the annotation feature and has been playing without the benefit of my comments).

A very satisfying move stepping out of the pin (finally) threatening c5 connecting rooks and exerting additional control on the e4 square via the diagonal.  The white queen is potentially heading for c3 after which it will be difficult for black to defend his weak pawn on e5.

Hi everyone!

Here again Operation Joblock has become my Expert opponents' chief nemesis.  It has sentenced about 10 out of 13 of such opponents to many hours of head scratching teeth gnashing (so much so they may well need a visit to my buddy The Dentist ere long!) before they either hit the offer draw button or click on the yes button in response to my draw offer or in the case of the Master Mater he decided to try and sac material before he in turn ended up allowing a draw by repetition.  This MT starts off with the Mason Variation of the Queen Pawn Opening which is 1.d4 d5 and 2. Bf4.  My opponent decided to develop a piece with 2. ..... Nf6.  Gameknot analysis is provided here: http://gameknot.com/analyze-board.pl?bd=15195165&fb=1&rnd=0.849941270083969
4. Nd2 - if black should plonk his knight on e4 then I can trade it off immediately.
6. ..... Bd6 - both sides develop their pieces and black offers an exchange of bishops.  The DB advises against immediate exchange of prelates however.
9. Ne5 - this knight move leads to a series of minor piece exchanges.
11. Nxe5 - one knight replaces another on e5.
14. ...... Qxd6 - now all the minor pieces but the light square bishops have been traded off.  The position looks roughly equal.
15. 0-0 - I decided to tuck Henry away on the kingside.
16. ...... a5 - allo allo - here comes a queenside pawn storm.  I now decided to shift all my major pieces over to the queenside after black decided to do likewise.
18. ..... Kf7 - even though the queens and both sets of rooks are still on the board black brings his king out for the endgame.  With my position all closed up Glenda cannot take advantage of this.

19. Qc1 - I certainly do feel that there is gonna be a major piece stouche on the a and b columns so Glenda moves to c1 to protect the b2 pawn (hence her sobriquet Glenda The Defender!) and to ensure that black will not be able to take control of either the open a and b columns when the a and b pawns are traded off.

20. Bd1 - this move looks passive but Fou Leblanc controls both the d1-a4 and the d1 to h5 diagonals.  This will be of some significance a few moves on.  Please note that black has all bar one of his pawns on the same colour square as his bishop.  These pawns will hem him in haha!

24. Qxa1 - after the rooks have been exchanged Glenda takes control of the open a file.  Black tries to contest the b column by moving the Wicked Witch of the West onto that file.  But never fear my stalwart defender Glenda has this all sussed and covered.  Her better half Henry edges towards the centre.  I intend a move such as g3 and moving Henry to g2.  This solidifies my position making it very hard to break down.  From a seemingly open position that Joblock strikes again!  On moving Henry to f1 I decided to offer a draw here.  Gameknot Analysis showed the position to be slightly in favour of black so it was a good draw offer netting me a handy 6 rating points keeping my rating in the high 1700s.  Hope you have had a nice weekend all of you and a good read.  Bye for now - Joanne

My name is Jason Capablanca and I am 9. I am going to make an analysis for you on my game against Strikerx. I do not make many analysis for you to read because now I am playing a lot of real hard players and my games do not look so good any more. And I do not play e4 very much here any more because then I have to know a lot of different openings and I am going to a hard school so I do not have time to study openings so much until summer time. I always do my best and I do not quit. I am writing this analysis because the French Defense is very hard to beat and I had to study with my coach Mr. Marble a lot last year to know how to play it when I went to the Olympiad last year. Maybe this will help you.

Nd2 breaks a lot of rules. I learned this last year. Black is also breaking a lot of opening rules so it is okay for White to break rules too. White can play 3. exd4 (exchange variation) 3. Nc3 or 3. e5. Nc3 and e5 are hard for White to hold onto the pawns in the middle and exd4 looks good but it does not get an advantage for White. It helps Black get his c8 Bishop out. Black wants White to play e5 so he can start attacking d4. My move is for the Tarrasch variation. Sometimes this Knight goes all the way to f3 so there are lots of pieces defending d4. That happened in this game.

4. e5 I like this variation because it makes Black waste another move with the Knight and Black must decide where to put the Knight. It always should go to d7 so it can help Black play c5 to attack the pawn on d4. But the extra moves let me get my pieces out.
I only have one chance to get this Bishop out. After that Black will attack my pawn on d4 and I will not have time to take him out again.
c5 This is the attack on the center Black is supposed to make. And it is why I played Nd2. You do not see why yet. But you will.

This is the best I think. When Black takes the pawn on d4 it will be replaced with another pawn. That is important to control the middle with pawns and to keep the extra space the e5 pawn has given me.
6. ... Nc6 Do you see how many pieces Black can aim at d4? It is hard to find enough defenders. That is why I played Nd2. You will see why.
7. Ne2 This is why I had to get my f Bishop out on move 5. I must develop this Knight to e2 so that I can have lots of defenders for d4.

7. ... c4?! This is a mistake. It is not part of the opening. But it is not a mistake because of that. It is a mistake because all of the French Defense depends on Black taking the pawns in the middle. Do you see how all of Black's pieces are on the Queen side? I saw this and I was confused. How can Black get his pieces out in the game if they are trapped behind his pawns on the Queen side?
8. ... b5 Now I think I see. He is changing his attack to the back of the pawn chain. he si going to try to aim at c3. But his pieces do not work so good to do this.

10. f4 I can not let Black do all of the attacking. If I do he will find a way to win. So I will try to open up the pawns in front of Blacks King. He is not developed and his King is not safe. So maybe I can get him in the center.
This makes all of the dark squares on the King side good for my Bishop.

11. Nf3 This move is made most of the time to give another defender to d4. That is why I made Nd2 at the beginning. See how both Knights defend d4? I do not need that now but my Knight is in the way of the Bishop and I am going to attack his King side so It should go over there anyway.

12. Be3 Maybe this is not so good a move. But if he takes my pawn on c3 I will take with my pawn on b2 and I will be able to control the open b file because my Rooks and Queen are all working together now. So I did my best to find a move to help make him not want to take c3. But I think maybe Ng3 would be good.

14. f5 see I waited too long for Ng3 and he is getting his pieces working together before I can play f5. I was trying my hardest but he has a rating over 1700 and he is a real good player. So I was afraid maybe I made this into a draw and it would not help the team win the match.

14. ... gxf5! I hoped he would take with the e pawn. Then I could play 15. Bh6 bxc3 16. bxc3 Bf8 17. Qc1 and he does not dare take my Bishop because my Queen will take back and I will be able to attack his King side. But this way he get's an open file for his Rook. And it will aim at my King.
I am hoping to get on f6

I do not just want to guard. I want to attack. I was hoping I could play Ng7+. That would leave me a lot of good tactics. His King would move to f8 and then I could play Nxe6!! which is a discoverd check on the King so I would win the Queen.

16. ... Qb6! You see he is a good player. He knows what I am trying to do. He could have played Bf8 and I would have played Qd2. And I do not get to win his Queen this way either. When I was playing before Knelica would let me play easier players and this would work but now my tricks do not work. This is not so bad though. Now the Queen is really trapped behind her pawns on the Queen side.
Never leave your King in front of a enemy Rook unless you have no choice.
Ba6. He is connecting his big pieces.
See. He must get his King out of the way. He is trying to get his big pieces on the open file.

19. Ng5! Now Knights are real mean when they are up towards the front. So I am getting them way up front. They will take away all of the squares for his pieces. So he can not let me leave them there. He must trade them away as fast as he can.
20. Bxg5+ He is a good player and he will not let me keep my Knights up forward. He knows to trade them. So I do not get so good an advantage.

22. Bxf6 Now I do not get to have any Knights. This is bad because there are lots of pawns on the board and Bishops are not so good when there are so many pawns in the way. Now I must do what Black wants me to do. I must make pawns go away. So I have to find a good way.
His doing what he planned but I have two defenders on g2 and he can not get any more attackers there. So I am not so worried.

My White squared Bishop is not very good because of his pawn on f5 so I am going to give it a job to do. When there are no ways to win pieces my coach says make your pieces better. It is going to make his Rooks go backwards and stay behind his pawns. You see? His Bishop is trapped. So His Knight is trapped. Even his Queen is trapped. So If I make his Rooks go backwards he does not have a way to get me.

Ashleyanderson has been asking me to teach him how to play the caro-kann so lets see how he does.

this is almost automatic. Other tries are Nd2(hypermodern) e5(advanced) or exd5(exchange)

3. e5 has had a bit of a resurgance in the resent past. Against 3. e5 I recommend attacking white's centre right away with 3. ...c5. 

3. exd5 is very similar to the exchange varation in the french is of no real threat to black. Although he needs to watch out for possible attack along the light square weakness. white will often try moves like Nb5 Qa4 etc. These are paired with early ...Bd7 and ...a6

This is the mainline caro-kann varation. Black has other options should as
...Nd7 ...Nf6.

...Nd7 is my favoraite and I believe black's strongest defence against e5 capture. But in this line black has to becareful of playing the early ...h6 because of the weakness on g6 and light sqaures.

most top players prefer this move over the sharp Ng5. Although ig white is going to play for a serious advantage then this is the only move. The Ng3 is more solid and positional in nature. It's tactical idea is to support the h2-h4-h5 push.

one of whites main strategic ideas is to control e5 with knight. Thus the vast majority of games revolve around a battle for e5. Strategically speaking if white can gain control of the e5 square then black will almost always lose. 

So from black's point of view is critical to maintain the balance of power of e5. However black is not without his resources since d5 can become a very strong point for a knight. Plus once white plays Ne5 black can most of the time undermine it by playing ...c5 or f6 under certain circumstances.

...Nf6 is ok beacuse it gains a tempo but basically hands over the e5 square for white. After this it's very hard to avoid being squeezed. I believe the main moves are ...Nd7 or ...e6 . The idea is that eventually black will be able to break free with either ...e5 or ...c5.

There is a threat to this move quite simply to trap the bishop which is very often a target in the Caro-Kann. The main line continues 6. ... h6 7. Nf3 Nd7 8. h5 Bh7 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 after which white gets a tidy position where black is still restricted. 

But from black's perspective the exchange for his weakest bishop for white's strongest bishop is a strategic victory. So in this away the caro-kann has a major advantage over the french in that the LSB is not a liablity.
providing a retreat square for the bishop

one of the ways that white tries to gain the advantage is to occupy e5 with the knight. For most players it is a matter of when. Some like to occupy early while others like to hold out for a clear break. I played 8. Ne5 to setup a trap for Ashleyanderson's learning benefit. 

The disadvantage of playing Ne5 early is that it can be easily undermined with ...c5 Nd7 ...or f6

?
This natural looking move is serious mistake by Ashelyanderson. Because he misses the threat. The threat is Nxg6! which causes serious weaknesses in black defence.

The only correct move is ...Bh7.

If you play ...h6 early it is important to know the how and when...h6 is to be played. As there is a very familar trap in the caro-kann. 

1.e4 c6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 dxe4 4.Nxe4 and now instead of Bf5 black might play 4...Nd7 if so then this is the line 5.Ng5 now it is tempting to play h6 but it's a mistake because after h6 then 6.Ne6(if fxe6 then 7.Qh5+ g6 8.Qxg6#) 6...Qb6 7.Nxf8 Nxf8 8.Nf3 with the advantage getting back to the right line 5...Ngf6 6.Bd3 e6 (if 6...h6 then 7.Ne6 fxe6 and 8.Bg6#) 7.N1f3 Bd6 8.Qe2 h6 9.Ne4 Nxe4 10.Qxe4 Nf6 11.Qe2 b6 12.Bd2 Bb7 13.0-0-0 Qc7 if 13...o-o then g4! opening lines on the enemy king

maybe ...Nb6 is better in order to give d7 as a flight square for the king

if 13. ...e5 then 14. Bxe5+ Nxe5 15. dxe5+ Kc7 16. exf6 Bd6 is nasty for black.

17. ...Ke5 18. Qe3+ Ne4 19. Qd4+ Kf4 20. Qxe4#

I guess because I have played the caro-kann for most of my chess career I have not taken the time to weight the required degree of strategic ideas that are employed. In truth it is one of black's most solid replies to 1. e4. However it is an advanced defensive line for black because accurate play and a clear uderstanding of the strategic mofits are required to maintain the balance. It requires strong memorization and familarity of the many openning lines. 

The flip side is that if you like to play the french then many of the ideas employed by white and black will be familar to you. So the jump for you will not be as great. I am glad that Ashleyanderson played the way he did because I hoped he learned a valueable lesson in the most dangerous line attacking theme that white has which is the kingside attack on g6.
